      <hedline>
        <hl1>Southern Hog Farms</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>National Pork Producers Council chief executive Alan Tank letter on Gail Collins's May 2 column defends North Carolina hog farms, citing improvements in odor control and water treatment</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''And in This Corner, Big Pork,'' by Gail Collins (column, May 2): Ms. Collins refers to ''the smell and environmental impact'' of hog farms located in North Carolina. Since March 1999, when a new law went into effect, state inspectors have responded to 200 odor complaints and have cited only one farm.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''And in This Corner, Big Pork,'' by Gail Collins (column, May 2): Ms. Collins refers to ''the smell and environmental impact'' of hog farms located in North Carolina. Since March 1999, when a new law went into effect, state inspectors have responded to 200 odor complaints and have cited only one farm.</p>
        <p>Twenty-six hog farms were flooded during Hurricane Floyd, but so were 209 municipal and industrial waste water treatment sites, 3,900 underground storage tanks, 171 Superfund sites, numerous auto junkyards and many other industrial sites. Ninety-eight percent of hog lagoons in North Carolina, which use the same treatment technology as thousands of American municipalities, remained untouched by the storm waters.</p>
        <p>ALAN  TANK  Chief Executive  National Pork Producers Council  Washington, May 3, 2000</p>
      </block>
